Description: Gawkk.com is a community-based social video sharing website that specializes in allowing people to collect and share videos with their
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: Gawkk.com is a community-based social video sharing website that specializes in allowing people to collect and share videos with their friends. Gawkk differs from other video sites, such as YouTube and Metacafe, because it does not host videos directly but instead lists videos from any hosting site on the web and displays the embedded videos in public channels created by the community. The site gets its videos from user-submission of the video URL or embed code, selected RSS feeds and selected web crawling. Gawkk organizes videos around channels, and members can subscribe to public channels that group videos in chronological order relative to a particular topic, such as a TV show, movie, celebrity, musical artist, comedian, etc. Members can save videos to their own personal video channel, follow other members' channels and share their saved videos with friends that follow them back, similar to the web service Twitter. Gawkk also includes other social community features, such as the ability to vote videos up or down, with videos that receive the most votes being promoted to the home page for the entire community to see, much like the news site digg. The privately-held company was founded by Gary Culliss and Thomas Mango in 2007 and is headquartered in New York, NY.
Industry Groups: Apps, Community and Lifestyle, Media and Entertainment, Software, Video

Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: Search, Win & Help Causes.   KindCoins is a search engine that combines elements of social gaming with cause support.  Leveraging Yahoo's search platform, KindCoins enables users to win cash donations to specified causes, as well as KindCoins while searching the web.   KindCoins are a virtual currency that users collect and convert into 'Acts of Kindness'.  These acts include things such as give a meal to someone in need, plant a tree, help prevent animal cruelty, provide clean water, etc.  Each act represents a micro-donation to an affiliated charitable organization.  KindCoins funds these actions by allocating 50% of their revenues towards charitable contributions. The site is heavily integrated into Facebook and includes a number of social elements.  KindCoins is trying to make something we do every day, i.e. search the web, more fun, engaging and socially meaningful.
